<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[+]&nbsp;Overall</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[-]&nbsp;Overall</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>I&#8230;.don't really like this. I like what you're trying to do; but the actual execution feels all over the place: there's so much jumping around topics and themes that the core narrative feels muddier than it should.</p>
<p>Decisions like not introducing -2 until the midpoint, instead of mentioning it explicitly in both the Description and the Discovery contribute to this: it has a feeling of introducing new elements to force character growth to occur; whereas if all the pieces had been laid out at the start, you could just, have the characters react: the whole thing around -1 being the passenger for the shadow can come up naturally when the interviewer asks about the painting, instead of in this weird forced way.</p>
<p>The disappearance of Agent Wolf is a like, technically interesting plot thread that never feels like it goes anywhere: Wolf is brought up immediately as they disappear so we don't really get invested in bringing them back, but other than a token question to Thomas in the one interview, it's never really explored in any way and it really feels like it could be cut: the painting doesn't need to be made explicitly anomalous, it could be made interesting and asked about purely from the discovery log noting SCP-XXXX was watching it.</p>
<p>I think though the core issue from the storytelling is that all the interesting stuff is in the relation between Thomas and Clarence, but there's barely any times where they actually interact in a tangible way: the discovery and the short video log being the only real times; the first interview kinda does but in a disconnected way where the shadow is definitely interacting with Clarence but not in a way that we, the reader, can grok and so it doesn't really add to their relationship. And so the arc feels rushed: there's never really a chance for this to establish what their relationship is like for the reader as a baseline really, or for us to get a feel for their characters; and so when this relationship is shifted up by Thomas confessing to Clarence, we don't really have a way to predict what this will do. The other problem is that the entire 'revelation, fallout, attempt to reconcile' thing takes place in 500 words: it never really gets the time it needs to show how this affects either of the characters or for them to tangibly grow as a result of this; and so it feels&#8230;lacking.</p>
<p>I can definitely see this being rewritten to work better but&#8230;it feels to me like it'd need a really thorough editing pass where you really consider how the story flows a lot more and then really figure out how you can best convey the flow.</p>
<p>In it's current state, this would be a -1 from me, and I would guess most other readers would feel the same way.</p>
</div>
